<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-292-957  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 292 957.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Jan 31 1989 v3 n5 p49(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MacWEEK Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Discovery Software buys Studiotronics in a flash. (StudiotronicsInc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Whitmer, Clair.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Discovery Software (acquisitions and mergers)Studiotronics Inc. (acquisitions and mergers).andO;Topic:     AcquisitionCompaniesInvestments.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Discovery Software buys Studiotronics in a flashandM;SAN FRANCISCO -- It was a classic computer industry tale of see it, want it,buy it.andM;Annapolis, Md.-based Discovery Software came to Macworld Expo to sell itspopular game Arkanoid.andP;  But when Discovery President Rick Ross happened by ademonstration of products from Studiotronics Inc. of Winter Park, Fla., hewas impressed.andM;So he bought the company.andM;Studiotronics came to the expo with its first set of retail products,including ColorSet, a system that uses software and physical RGB (red, green,blue) filters to convert images scanned on gray-scale scanners into colorimages.andM;Within three days, the two companies had signed preliminary papers forDiscovery to purchase 65 percent of the equity in Studiotronics.andM;Although Studiotronics is now a &quot;Discovery Software company,&quot; it will retainits Florida-based offices and its management.andP;  Discovery will providemarketing and package design expertise, as well as development help on theColorSet interface.andM;The companies hope to have an improved version out within three months.andP;  Thisnew release will include driver support for &quot;all major market scanners,&quot;scanner front-end software and speed improvements, said Ross.andO;</TEXT></DOC>